Yeah, here's what I'm seeing in the route:

```ts
export async function DELETE(req: Request) {
  const userId = await getUserId(req);
  await db.user.delete({ where: { id: userId } });
  return new Response(null, { status: 204 });
}
```

That's it. One line. Hard delete, nothing else. No Stripe teardown, no confirmation, no grace window. Maya probably tapped it by accident — the button is right in the middle of the settings page.

Output:
```
app/api/account/route.ts:12:  await db.user.update({ where: { id: userId }, data: { deletedAt: new Date() } });
app/api/account/route.ts:13:  await sendDeletionConfirmationEmail(user.email, user.id);
```

That's it in the deletion handler — soft-delete and email. No Stripe calls at all. Meanwhile in the webhook:
```
app/api/webhooks/stripe/route.ts:41:  const user = await db.user.findFirst({ where: { stripeCustomerId: event.data.object.customer } });
app/api/webhooks/stripe/route.ts:42:  if (!user) throw new Error('User not found...');
```

So the webhook assumes the user still exists. When the subscription renewal fires, it tries to find the user, fails, throws.

content.text:
This is a serious compliance gap. The fix is not to change the cascade rule to `Restrict` — that would just make the deletion fail with a FK constraint error. The fix is an explicit anonymize-in-place step that runs BEFORE the user record is purged.

Here's the constraint we need to capture: Records subject to tax-record retention (invoices, payments, refunds, tax filings) must be anonymized, not deleted, when their associated user is purged. User-identifying fields (name, email, billing address) are overwritten with `[deleted user]`; the financial data and timestamps remain intact.

We're calling this `con-anonymize-not-delete-tax-held-2026-03-04`. It applies any time an account purge would otherwise cascade-delete a record that legal/finance has flagged as held-for-retention — current list: Invoice, Payment, Refund, TaxFiling, OrgInvoice (see `lib/retention/held.ts` which we should create).

The fix in `beginAccountDeletion`:
```ts
await db.invoice.updateMany({
  where: { userId },
  data: {
    userName: '[deleted user]',
    userEmail: '[deleted user]',
  },
});
```

This preserves the financial data and timestamps (which are what the IRS actually wants) while removing the PII. The IRS doesn't need Maya's name and email — they need the amounts, dates, and transaction IDs.

For the Prisma schema, change `onDelete: Cascade` to `onDelete: SetNull` or `onDelete: Restrict` on retention-sensitive tables. `SetNull` means a purge attempt will set the FK to null rather than cascade-deleting; the anonymize step should run first to clear PII before the FK is nulled.

Here's the complete `beginAccountDeletion` implementation that honors all four decisions/constraints we've captured in this incident chain:

```ts
export async function beginAccountDeletion(userId: string) {
  const user = await db.user.findUniqueOrThrow({ where: { id: userId } });

  // 1. Soft-delete with 30-day grace (dec-soft-delete-30day-grace-2026-02-18)
  //    Never call db.user.delete() from a request handler.
  await db.user.update({
    where: { id: userId },
    data: { deletedAt: new Date() },
  });

  // 2. Anonymize tax-held records — GDPR-eager, IRS-safe
  //    (con-anonymize-not-delete-tax-held-2026-03-04)
  await db.invoice.updateMany({
    where: { userId },
    data: { userName: '[deleted user]', userEmail: '[deleted user]' },
  });

  // 3. Archive Stripe customer — do NOT call stripe.customers.del()
  //    (con-stripe-customer-archive-2026-02-22)
  if (user.stripeCustomerId) {
    await stripe.subscriptions
      .list({ customer: user.stripeCustomerId, status: 'active' })
      .then((subs) =>
        Promise.all(
          subs.data.map((sub) =>
            stripe.subscriptions.cancel(sub.id, { invoice_now: false, prorate: false })
          )
        )
      );
    await stripe.customers.update(user.stripeCustomerId, {
      metadata: { archived: 'true', archived_at: new Date().toISOString() },
    });
  }

  // 4. Suppress on mailing list — do NOT delete the member
  //    (con-mailing-list-suppress-not-delete-2026-03-11)
  await mailchimp.lists.setListMember(MARKETING_LIST_ID, hashEmail(user.email), {
    status: 'unsubscribed',
    status_if_new: 'unsubscribed',
  });

  // 5. Send email-link confirmation (dec-confirm-via-email-link-2026-02-18)
  await sendDeletionConfirmationEmail(user.email, user.id);

  await auditLog('account.deletion_requested', { userId });
}
```

Each comment cites the substrate rule ID. Every line is a rule firing. This is exactly what Contract IDE will surface when the PM writes the contract for this feature — the five substrate rules are the implementation spec.
